Prove $0, \frac{1}{2}, 0, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{2}{3}, 0, \frac{1}{4}, \frac{2}{4}, ...$ equidistributed in $[0, 1)$. A sequence of numbers $\xi_1, \xi_2, \xi_3, ...$ in $[0, 1)$ is said to be equidistributed if for every
  interval $(a, b) \subset [0, 1)$ $$\lim\limits_{N\to\infty} \frac {\bigl|\{1\le n\le N: \xi_n \in (a, b)\}\bigr|} {N}
= b-a$$ It's from Chapter 4 in the book Fourier Analysis: An Introduction
